    "note": "Measured on a shared x86-64 Linux cloud container (karac from current main b4929c8), NOT the corpus's Apple M5 Pro. FAIRNESS NOTE (load-bearing): the kata builds DP rows with Vec.new()+push (a GROWING dynamic array); the first mirror draft used fixed STACK arrays in C/Rust/Go (zero alloc) which made kara look ~6x slow — an apples-to-oranges heap-Vec-vs-stack-array comparison. Every mirror here instead builds rows by APPENDING to a growing dynamic array (Rust Vec::push, Go append, C realloc-doubling, Python list.append), matching kara's Vec. At EQUAL semantics kara is FASTEST: kara 2153 < c 2354 (realloc) < rust 2860 (Vec::push) < go 3640 (append). This is allocation/realloc-dominated (all 2-3.6s), so it measures growing-Vec throughput, not pure DP compute — a fixed/pre-sized-array discipline would be ~6x faster for all (stack-C measured ~358ms) but is a different data structure than the kata's Vec. The row length is statically knowable, so a pre-sizing codegen opt (kara's Vec.new()+counted-push -> pre-sized fill, ledger B-2026-07-08-7, currently REVERTED for regressing #63) would cut allocation for kara. Re-run on the M5 to fold comparable numbers into the corpus tables."
